      <aside class="calc-sidebar">
        <div class="card sidebar-card">
          <h2>What is a square root?</h2>
          <p>The square root of a number is the value that, when multiplied by itself, gives that number. For example, √25 = 5 because 5 × 5 = 25. Square roots and powers are inverse operations — squaring a number and taking its square root cancel each other out.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card sidebar-card">
          <h3>Frequently asked questions</h3>
          <details>
            <summary>What is the square root of 2?</summary>
            <p>The square root of 2 is approximately 1.41421356. It is an irrational number — its decimal digits go on forever without repeating. It is the length of the diagonal of a unit square.</p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>Can you take the square root of a negative number?</summary>
            <p>Not in the real number system. The square root of a negative number is an imaginary number (using the imaginary unit i, where i² = −1). This is part of complex number mathematics.</p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>What is the difference between x² and √x?</summary>
            <p>x² (x squared) multiplies x by itself. √x (square root of x) finds the number that when squared gives x. They are inverse operations: √(x²) = x and (√x)² = x for positive x.</p>
          </details>
        </div>
